        <h4>GeoBoost2 is a public health informatics application for finding the location of infected hosts for the purposes of phylogeography and epidemiology. 
            It uses state-of-the-art natural language processing (NLP) methods to extract and disambiguate geographical locations from scientific articles.
        </h4>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <h3>What kind of inputs does it accept?</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><u>GenBank Accession IDs</u> : Given a list of GenBank Accession IDs, GeoBoost2 extracts the location information from the GenBank record.
                  When the location information is not at a sufficient level, it retrieves the associated PubMed article (when available) and attemps to extract
                  all locations from the said article. (see PubMed IDs below)
          </li>
          <li><u>PubMed IDs</u> : Given a list of PubMed IDs, GeoBoost2 first attemps to retrieve the full-text article from PubMed Central Open Access subset. 
                  When the full text isn't available the abstract is retrieved. GeoBoost2 then extracts all geographical locations and respective contexts from the article's text.
          </li>
          <li><u>Raw Text</u> : Given the raw text from an article, GeoBoost2 extracts all geographical locations from the text.
          </li>
        </ul>
